Viewer Discretion Advised!

3. Motorcycle accident while wearing sandals 
4. Rattlesnake bite 🐍

.
.

node.text:
During the American Civil War, serious attempts were made to reconstruct the faces of soldiers injured in battle.
Repost from: @drlindseyfitzharris 
. 
Photos 1 & 2: 
Pictured here is Private Roland Ward, who underwent several operations WITHOUT anesthetic to repair his face in the 1860s! 
.
Photos 3 & 4: 
The most skillful surgeon to emerge during this period was Gurdon Buck, who helped repair the face of Private Carleton Burgan after a gangrenous infection destroyed his upper mouth, palate, right cheek & eye. With the help of a dentist named Thomas B. Gunning, Buck was able to reconstruct parts of Burgan’s face using rudimentary skin grafts and flap techniques shown in photo 4. 
.
Photo 5: 
Buck was one of only a handful of surgeons willing to attempt such risky procedures as infection rates during this period were staggering. Most soldiers were left with terrible wounds, gaps, and missing tissue in their faces. When Private Joseph Harvey was hit by a shell fragment, he found employment as a night watchman, and died a few years later.
.
.
Images credit: National Museum of Civil War Medicine and National Museum of Health & Medicine.

node.text:
⚠️Intraocular foreign body⚠️👁
This case involves a malfunctioning piece of machinery that shot a metal washer into a workers eye. Unfortunately he was not wearing any eye protection or safety glasses at the time of the incident. 
.
Luckily the man was taken to a hospital and the foreign body was safely removed. He did not have any long term effects or vision loss. 
.
Even though this man was extremely lucky to have no lasting damage, vision loss and eye injury are very common with Intraocular injuries. 
.
Always remember to protect your eyes wear safety glasses! 👓

node.text:
⚠️Necrotizing finger infection⚠️
(Warning: viewer discretion advised for second video)
.
This case involves a necrotizing infection. A necrotizing infection is a rare but very severe type of bacterial infection that can occur when bacteria enters the body through a break in the skin. It can destroy the muscles, skin, and underlying tissue. The word "necrotizing" refers to something that causes body tissue to die.
.
In the first video you can clearly see the infected finger and a red stripe of lymphangitis (inflammation of the lymphatic system) traveling up the arm. 
.
In the second video, you see the removal of nail from the infected finger. The patient also underwent treatment of skin debridement followed by IV antibiotics.
.
.
Video credit: @drdboca 
#surgery #medcial #traumasurgeon #infection #medicine #nurse #medic #anatomy #amputation #emergencymedicine #extremitytrauma

3. Caught in a riptide and thrown into a large rock on ocean floor

6. Bucked from a horse

.

node.text:
Hungry hungry Flatworm! 🪱
This video shows a multicellular Gieysztoria catching and eating a unicellular organism. 

(Magnification x100)🔬
.
Gieysztoria can push out their pharynx to quickly catch its food. 
.
Unicellular organisms are made up of only one cell that carries out all of the functions needed by the organism, while multicellular organisms use many different cells to function. Unicellular organisms can include bacteria, protists, and yeast.

node.text:
Oddly satisfying to watch!👀
.
What you’re seeing in this video is called Sclerotherapy.
It involves injecting a solution directly into varicose and spider veins. 
The sclerotherapy solution causes the vein to scar, forcing blood to reroute through healthier veins. The collapsed vein is reabsorbed into local tissue and eventually fades.

node.text:
Baby born in the car! 👶🏼 
In this incredible video, a woman gives birth to her baby boy in the car while her husband is driving her to the hospital. Mom and baby were both healthy and doing great when they arrived at the hospital. 
.
Though television shows and movies depict births in cars to happen frequently, they actually aren’t that common. 
The CDC reported that approximately 60,000 American babies are born outside of hospitals each year. Out-of-hospital deliveries represent about 1.5 percent of births in the United States. 
Of those births, over 90 percent took place in a residence or a birthing center. That leaves only a slim percentage of the overall births taking place in America to have possibly occurred in cars. 
.
A study done in 2011 showed that out of roughly 3,000,000 births in the United States, only about 6,000 of those babies were born while their mothers were in transit.

node.text:
Can you spot what’s wrong in this picture before swiping or reading the caption? 👀
.
.
@northamericanrescue Great case study from @penntacticalsolutions
•
This is a rare case but one that deserves some attention. 
Background: Patient was found unresponsive but breathing (unknown if agonal) after a self-inflicted GSW to the right temple. EMS responded and a BLS crew arrived on scene. Assessment revealed obvious damage to the temple, however, no obvious facial deformity was noted. As part of resuscitative efforts an NPA was placed prior to ALS arrival. Patient was intubated by ALS and subsequently transported to trauma center where the patient was eventually pronounced deceased.  X-Ray determined that the initial NPA had been inserted into the cranial cavity. 
Discussion: This case brings up several teaching points:
1.	NPAs are contraindicated where there is clear fluid coming out of the nostrils that may be cerebrospinal fluid (Presence of CSF can be tested using gauze and the “halo” test), if there is suspected skull fracture or if there is massive facial trauma. 
2.	The NPA should be inserted with the device at a 90-degree angle to the face. If the NPA is inserted correctly, the chances of it hitting the basilar part of the skull is minimal. A common mistake is following the angle of the nares. 

#upyournosewitharubberhose #airwaymanagement #tccc #paramedic #emt #nasalairway #airway #trauma #ambulance #whenyouseeit #medical
